<subSubSection id="C726D6A8328C5006A04963583372DEC4" pageId="0" pageNumber="123" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="0C1CC56C10203F44DF74EDFC2E747C3C" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5E6D113F39484BB19EA564FAFD8BF966" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="939D8E2247CF12CD677CF59DF68E87CB" authority="Spinola, 1841" authorityName="Schenkling" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Tillicera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tillicera soror" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="soror">
<emphasis id="F41BCF594E1E5C42B452E343AA1B8DC0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Tillicera soror</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Schenkling, 1902, but distinguished by the following characteristics: antennomere VI-X gradually broadened; metatibiae apically extended to a broad spine; posterior margin of abdominal ventrite V, with broadly V-shaped emargination; phallobase notched at apical 1/5 of total length of tegmen (vs. 
<taxonomicName id="161481D18BAC3EAA434CC564E292564C" class="Insecta" genus="T." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="T. soror" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="soror">
<emphasis id="A841595E35857189FC3E03C51CBBA6BD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">T. soror</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: antennomere VIII-IX gradually broadened; hind tibiae not prominent at apex; posterior margin of abdominal sternite V broadly U-shaped and truncate; phallobase deeply notched at apical 1/3).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4DB4BBEB86541C33D83A8E234CC58BAC" pageId="0" pageNumber="123" type="description">
<paragraph id="D29C1E7F0295FC80831E8F13DA11B73C" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B52B23C0184A082EF3C3390A7F7A971" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">
<emphasis id="E6AE275D46E12773063AB90F06C305D2" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Male.</emphasis>
Head, antennomeres IV-XI, base of pronotum and legs brownish black; antennomeres I-III and pronotum reddish. Elytra black except for reddish area near basal suture and yellowish area at basal 1/4 near lateral margin. Head at apex and legs covered with white setae; basal 1/2 of head and pronotum with mingled white and black setae; elytra densely vested with yellowish setae obliquely at suture of basal 1/3 and transversally at lateral margin basal 1/4 and apical 1/4, the remainder vested with black setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DB27F4ACC1246D9B1839D6B47915F7A5" captionStart="Figures 1–12" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 12. Habitus of Tillicera species 1 Tillicera auratofasciata 2 T. aurivillosa 3 T. bibalteata 4 T. callosa 5, 6 T. cleroides 7, 8 T. hirsuta 9, 10 T. ihlei 11, 12 T. javana. Scale bars 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures1-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672265" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">10</figureCitation>
). This species has two color patterns: the first, antennomeres IV-XI, apex of pronotum, elytra except for area covered with yellowish setae, and legs black (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E5C0C9558D85A50290A3337811E18A06" captionStart="Figures 1–12" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 12. Habitus of Tillicera species 1 Tillicera auratofasciata 2 T. aurivillosa 3 T. bibalteata 4 T. callosa 5, 6 T. cleroides 7, 8 T. hirsuta 9, 10 T. ihlei 11, 12 T. javana. Scale bars 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures1-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672265" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">11</figureCitation>
); the second, head black; apical 1/4 of pronotum brownish black; elytral setae white and black (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="487E86BAD2305BAC46106A65846464B8" captionStart="Figures 1–12" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 12. Habitus of Tillicera species 1 Tillicera auratofasciata 2 T. aurivillosa 3 T. bibalteata 4 T. callosa 5, 6 T. cleroides 7, 8 T. hirsuta 9, 10 T. ihlei 11, 12 T. javana. Scale bars 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures1-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672265" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">12</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="701EEBD3813E039AB73386364FADDA86" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">
Head including eyes as wide as pronotum; labrum incised at middle; maxillary terminal palpomeres digitiform; labial terminal palpomeres widely triangular; postgular plate narrow. Antennomere I claviform; II compact; III twice as long as II; IV-X triangular, becoming gradually widened; V-IX (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="1F12F4F81739ABE020DC0AB833C3452A" captionStart="Figures 28–31" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 28 - 31. Antennae of Tillicera spp. (28 dorsal view 29 - 31 ventral view) 28 male antennomere XI of T. spinosa sp. nov. 29 female antennomere X of T. spinosa sp. nov. 30 female antennomeres VII-IX of T. spinosa sp. nov. 31 male antennomeres IV and V of T. callosa. Abbreviations: P pit-like sensillum SB an area of sensilla basiconica." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures28-31" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672268" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">30</figureCitation>
) with an area vested with sensilla basiconica; X (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7A0AB43930495D98FB7E37BF2A896213" captionStart="Figures 28–31" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 28 - 31. Antennae of Tillicera spp. (28 dorsal view 29 - 31 ventral view) 28 male antennomere XI of T. spinosa sp. nov. 29 female antennomere X of T. spinosa sp. nov. 30 female antennomeres VII-IX of T. spinosa sp. nov. 31 male antennomeres IV and V of T. callosa. Abbreviations: P pit-like sensillum SB an area of sensilla basiconica." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures28-31" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672268" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">29</figureCitation>
) with two areas vested with sensilla basiconica at apical margin in ventral view; XI (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C8820F885F4E7A8018DF2E9E72DAC294" captionStart="Figures 28–31" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 28 - 31. Antennae of Tillicera spp. (28 dorsal view 29 - 31 ventral view) 28 male antennomere XI of T. spinosa sp. nov. 29 female antennomere X of T. spinosa sp. nov. 30 female antennomeres VII-IX of T. spinosa sp. nov. 31 male antennomeres IV and V of T. callosa. Abbreviations: P pit-like sensillum SB an area of sensilla basiconica." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures28-31" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672268" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">28</figureCitation>
) with small pit-like sensillum in male.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CA26636A0A868E864CC60859D88F693B" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Pronotum slightly longer than wide, widest at middle, with fine dense punctures. Mesoventrite with short anterior process.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="17F381F03193409045D4B814485B5D65" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Elytra oblong, parallel sided, covered with ten striae; striae I and II absent before basal oblique yellow fascia; III-V or VII extending after middle, sometimes absent before basal oblique yellow fascia; VI or VIII-X rudimentary.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2682E726E8DA724DFDE2CA74EAB45555" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Profemora stouter than meso- and metafemora; punctation of meso- and metafemora denser than that of profemora. Tibiae short prominent at apex, with distinct longitudinal carina on dorsal and ventral surfaces; tibial spur formula 1-2-0; tarsal pulvillar formula 4-4-2; pro- and mesotarsomeres I and II with large lobed pulvilli; III and IV with large bilobed pulvilli; metatarsomeres I and II without pulvilli; III and IV with large bilobed pulvilli; claws with basal denticles.</paragraph>
<caption id="214FBC3AF6D5935B30FC451A1E61D1AB" doi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures36-40" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672270" pageId="0" pageNumber="123" start="Figures 36–40" startId="F6">
<paragraph id="24CA454106B129D5F398AFE7753E9654" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">
<emphasis id="95942993E8FD4455FD46BA0BA307147E" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Figures 36-40.</emphasis>
Male terminal parts and aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName id="AC0BF3D1B465CE4D57AD8F87EA0DDD47" authority="Spinola, 1841" authorityName="Gerstmeier &amp; Bernhard" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Tillicera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tillicera callosa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="callosa">
<emphasis id="B633FE8697A7ECB9FA38CD721AA3D7D3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Tillicera callosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="D8AB1E8E78EEE7E871BB64E700A1242F" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">36</emphasis>
pygidium 
<emphasis id="3104FF09743C2B8624F9949D6515EE82" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">37</emphasis>
ventrite VI 
<emphasis id="F1D9652A13CD411C0E8C917D4415494A" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">38</emphasis>
spicular fork 
<emphasis id="3B273EDE68A8F832CBBBFB08F09F6B77" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">39</emphasis>
tegmen in lateral (a), ventral (b) and dorsal (c) views 
<emphasis id="3B7C9B96AF0A2147F4208B47FE73B132" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">40</emphasis>
median lobe in lateral (a), ventral (b), and dorsal (c) views.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="1245FC3F3463683F1B9E0555C92057AB" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">
Abdominal ventrite V deeply emarginated at apical margin. Pygidium (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="65011B52DE006E5C3F794248651C5CAF" captionStart="Figures 41–50" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 41 - 50. Male terminal parts and aedeagus 41 - 45 Tillicera fortis sp. nov. 46 - 50 T. spinosa sp. nov. 41, 46 pygidium 42, 47 ventrite VI 43, 48 spicular fork 44, 49 tegmen in lateral (a), ventral (b) and dorsal (c) views 45, 50 median lobe in lateral (a), ventral (b), and dorsal (c) views." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures41-50" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672271" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">46</figureCitation>
) narrowly emarginated at apical margin; ventrite VI (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C26878D67827C41327BA4BF78DCC7F16" captionStart="Figures 41–50" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 41 - 50. Male terminal parts and aedeagus 41 - 45 Tillicera fortis sp. nov. 46 - 50 T. spinosa sp. nov. 41, 46 pygidium 42, 47 ventrite VI 43, 48 spicular fork 44, 49 tegmen in lateral (a), ventral (b) and dorsal (c) views 45, 50 median lobe in lateral (a), ventral (b), and dorsal (c) views." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures41-50" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672271" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">47</figureCitation>
) almost transverse at apical margin; spicular fork long (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8CC1D7735DC5468A88362A4CCFC73456" captionStart="Figures 41–50" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 41 - 50. Male terminal parts and aedeagus 41 - 45 Tillicera fortis sp. nov. 46 - 50 T. spinosa sp. nov. 41, 46 pygidium 42, 47 ventrite VI 43, 48 spicular fork 44, 49 tegmen in lateral (a), ventral (b) and dorsal (c) views 45, 50 median lobe in lateral (a), ventral (b), and dorsal (c) views." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures41-50" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672271" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">48</figureCitation>
), without intraspicular plate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4AECA0E338F46F82F6E7252422A9E6C5" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">
Tegmen (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="EDDAD97294F259FE1F70C1F86240F74E" captionStart="Figures 41–50" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 41 - 50. Male terminal parts and aedeagus 41 - 45 Tillicera fortis sp. nov. 46 - 50 T. spinosa sp. nov. 41, 46 pygidium 42, 47 ventrite VI 43, 48 spicular fork 44, 49 tegmen in lateral (a), ventral (b) and dorsal (c) views 45, 50 median lobe in lateral (a), ventral (b), and dorsal (c) views." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures41-50" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672271" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">49a-c</figureCitation>
) with dorsal and ventral sinus at apical 1/5; parameroid lobes tapered posteriorly at apex in lateral view; tegminal arms short, extending from middle to basal 1/4 of total length. Median lobe shorter than tegmen; plates with rows of denticles from apical 1/5 to 2/5 of total length on dorsal and ventral sides (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="CE87E34EBA5998ECF5F0B1C49AF6CCA6" captionStart="Figures 41–50" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 41 - 50. Male terminal parts and aedeagus 41 - 45 Tillicera fortis sp. nov. 46 - 50 T. spinosa sp. nov. 41, 46 pygidium 42, 47 ventrite VI 43, 48 spicular fork 44, 49 tegmen in lateral (a), ventral (b) and dorsal (c) views 45, 50 median lobe in lateral (a), ventral (b), and dorsal (c) views." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures41-50" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672271" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">50a-c</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E69ED3D1D6AD809C0D8638EAE9AEB151" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">
<emphasis id="0C6A861CC0872ED1A12C5804C38F60F7" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Female.</emphasis>
Similar to male but distinguished by antennomere XI without pit-like sensillum, tibial spur formula 1-2-2 and apex of metatibiae not extended to a broad spine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
